comment: This professor almost never used the book, and the way he grades the exams and homework is very inconsistent. He only returned 1 homework set out of the 12 we turned in for the semester. Avoid this professor at all costs, he really doesn't care about if his students gets it or not.
He is a good teacher. He is hard to understand at first but you get used to it as the semester goes on. He will help whenever needed and is a nice guy!

I didn't really have a problem with this TA or the class because I took pre-calc and calc in high school. The guy is kinda weird, and not a great teacher, but the class is mostly self-explanatory. He acted like we were stupid sometimes when we didn't want to answer him and laughed at us, but really you just laugh back. Do most of the homework...
TR is a great guy / teacher very enthusiastic and sometimes humorous.
You can't understand a single word that he says.. i learned more in the 50 minutes of recitation then i did the entire week of his teaching. Try to take another teacher.

Don't buy textbook Midterm is impossible, final is a cakewalk 2 papers with 0 instruction but are easy Her powerpoints look like they were made by a 3 year old Is probably the most unorganized and unclear prof at MSU Her TA didn't even know where I could find the instructions for an assignment Class is called "sports media" be "Sports history"
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: She has a lot of knowledge and experience. If you are struggling and reach out she will definitely help you.
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: Sue Carter is a great person. She's a good teacher and her homework assignments are easy. The tests are unbelievably difficult, but she may curve the grade if everyone doesn't do well. If you come to class, listen, participate and ask questions, you should skate out of there with a 3.0 or better. Great guest lectures in this class, too.

Prof. Carter likes what she does and is, overall, a nice person. The homework was easy and didn't happen that often. The tests are pretty much impossible (class high on the midterm was 78%) and count for 60% of your grade. She did curve it though, at least for us.

Sue is cool.  She is a fair grader.  She is a wealth of information and she loves to ramble on about pretty much anything.  Her classes are mandatory, remember that.  She'll give easy homework assignments and impossible tests. Make sure you study a lot for the tests.

Never take a class with Dr. McCrory!! She does not grade any papers within a reasonable amount of time. I only have had 5 assignments graded a week before the final. She is inconsistent with her grading and overall has a poor attitude in class. She does not know enough about the material to teach it. Take this class with another professor!

Never returned assignments on time. Lack of timely feedback severely affected the ability to learn much. Waited for 3 months to receive feedback. Very discouraged by her attitude and grading. Although some topics were taught well but feedback on assignments when returned was inconsistent. Would not recommend this course to anyone!

Horrible teacher. She discriminates on race and ethnicity. As an international student, I found her developing problems for me. I ended learning nothing from her. No I learnt one thing. Never take a class with her.

Took class in Spring 2008. Poor communicator. Told me one week from the end of the term that I wouldn't be passing her class even though I'd done all the work. It was like a slap in the face.  Her feedback was non-existent, so I had no idea she was going to "flunk" me. I re-took the class and got a 4.0 from a different instructor. Go figure.

I took this course with Dr. McCrory and learned nothing. She is quantitative-oriented, and she has no concept of qualitative research possibilities. She basically told me I couldn't do what my guidance committee had already approved for me in my dissertation preparation. When I explained my committee's actions to her, she yelled at me. Worthless.
Great teacher. I don't know what class these other people were in, but this was one of my best classes ever.

Wow, I see these other comments, and it must be from the same class I took. She made us do weekly homework, like we were in high school. If we did it "wrong", we had to do it over. Of course, she never told us what was "right". Other sections of this class actually let you work on a relevant research project, I'm told. What a waste of a semester.

She is pretty bad. I got a 4.0 in her class, because I kept my mouth shut, basically. Treats you like a child, makes you do busy work, teaches absolutely nothing. The less you say to her, the better. I was warned not to take her class, and I wish I had listened to the advice.

Worst professor in the CEPSE department, period. Took her 19 days to grade midterms; she even had a TA! Berated students who disagreed with her, even with no expertise in their field. Has an attendance policy in violation of department acceptance of working students. Class at her house TWICE; assumed friendly familiarity that was SO not there.

Since coming back to school after working for years, I have received nothing but A's for a solid year, so I'm not just happy that I got an easy A. For the first time I felt my tuition was well spent, and every time I went to class I learned something stimulating, and not just what you can puke out on a LSAT.  The world needs more profs like this.

shes not easy, and will not hand you a grade for crappy writing.But, she will be more than helpful in making sure you have all the tools you need to become a better writer. Shes a little intense, but very clear. Her jokes are great; shes very understand as long as she can tell you are trying.(longest paper is 7 pages, most are 3 to 4.)

Kelly was great! She was so funny, but really intense. The first week you will be scared out of your mind, but I really enjoyed her class. She grades 'hard' but will tell you she doesn't. Kelly is very willing to help if you go to office hours. My writing got a ton better with her! She is a stickler for rubrics though so be careful.
The best teacher you could ask for! She made class very interesting and always kept us laughing. I definitely improved in my writing
Really nice, but was not well organized with the class. Turned in stuff, and didn't get any grades back until after the final. But relatively easy class.
No Comments

I had an interest in philosophy... then I attended this class. Her lectures are confusing and non-explanatory, and her exams - though take home - hard. I find that I learned more about philosophy from stumbleupon than I did from this class. Avoid!

Ugh. Hated this class. She is the most difficult grader, telling me that I am not at all a good writer when writing in all my other classes is my strong point. I honestly couldn't wait to be done this class. It made me never want to take a philosophy class again...
frustrating class, papers not related to long, boring lectures.
Attendance counts A LOT!
boring
No Comments

Dr. Johnson is one of the best professors I have had at MSU.  He makes linguistics fun to learn and is always willing to meet with students and help them. He has a lot of energy in class and a great attitude.  If you get a chance to take a class with him I highly recommend it.

Once he was sick but didn't send an email saying that. Once the class was supposed to have started one of his TA's announced to the class (everyone was already there) that there was no lecture that day and that we could leave. Other than that, he was generally an alright professor.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: This class is only worth 2 credits and is actually a lot of work- project wise. The lectures are boring and pointless but you have to go to get points. The labs are fun but require a LOT of extra time to build robots, solar cars, etc. Fun course but you definitely have to put the work in.
Cool professor. Boring class and content really isn't necessary to learn. The

EGR 100 is pretty pointless, but Hinds is fine. There's an assignment in lecture every week, which makes you go, and is the only reason anyone would show up to lecture. The class is a lot of work for only 2 credits, but it's not that bad. It's mostly ran by TAs, and if you get a bad one it can be sort of rough especially if they grade harshly.

The class itself is boring and pointless but Hinds is a great professor. I misunderstood him in class and showed up to the final exam the day after it was held. I went to his office and explained himself and he let me take the exam right there. Any other professor, especially one with 500+ students, would have gave me a zero and caused me to fail.

The lectures are no problem - hw each time, go and you're good. Beware of Lab!  Group projects are the majority of your grade - get a bad group like me and you're doing all the work. You can get A's on everything but if your group fails to perform you won't get the A you're hoping for.
Mr. Hinds taught me everything I know about ethics. He's my hero. His class is awful.

The only reason to attend his lectures are for the iclicker, the lectures are usually common sense and he puts the slides on the class page. He talk's about professionalism but doesn't practice what he preaches. In the small group, the TA's lead the class and is much more engineer-friendly.
Very simple guy, gives you all powerpoints, only thing is he takes attendance and gives random quizes. mostly deal with TA's, just be responsible and you will ace the class...
He is a decent professor, but in this class you mainly deal with the T.A.s.
He really loves teaching this class. He has online lectures and makes them very fun to watch!! I loved having him as a professor!
he is very into what he is teaching and he trys really hard to make everyone interested in global change. However, you dont have a textbook and when it comes time for the test, its not always easy.
This professor grades her students like they know everything about sociolinguistics. So unless you're already a sociolinguistic genius, I really suggest not taking this class with this professor.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Graded by few things--Tough grader

comment: I like Dr. Wagner a lot. Although her lectures were often long & boring, I appreciated her enthusiasm for the course, her helpful nature, and her kind spirit. I do wish, though, that her lectures were more clear. Exams were difficult to prepare for b/c I never knew what was relevant info and what was excess, untested info -- even from recitation.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Suzanne is a doll. She is British, which I think is hilarious because she teaches Linguistics. But she knows her stuff and she wants you to know it too. She is super helpful and really wants you to think and participate. But if you're wrong, she doesn't shoot you down. Overall she has been one of my favorite professors here at MSU.
No Comments

EC 335 with Professor Menchik was typical EC course, class is just twice a week and random attendance days are marked by the TA (10% of grade is going to class). The tests were difficult, the multiple choice is difficult but the short answer isnt bad.  An ok teacher but a better person get to know him  go to office hours or just take good notes.
I took a 300 level Econ course with him, and never read the assigned text and got a 4.0. Just go to class and take good notes and it should be easy.

Seems like a nice, intelligent guy who would do great working at a firm, but he's seriously an awful teacher. The average grade hovers around a 2.5 and he has about an hour of office hours a week...so not really helpful there. Not very prepared either- he was short exams on both of our exam dates which (understandably) frustrated a lot of students.
She's very responsive to her students

He speaks french the entire time through out class, not to mention when he does speak little english it sounds like he is still speaking french! I do not suggest taking his class if you have never taken the French language before.

Great Professor. I have taken him twice, and unlike the past commenter, I think he has a very engaging class. It is not tough to contribute. He does expect a lot, but he is just such an awesome teacher. You should take his class!

Gave speech about the course being the toughest course at MSU, but it wasn't that bad. He adjusted the syllabus halfway through the term and cut out some texts and projects. Granted, this was summer semester. Exams were easy, but papers were graded tough. He had a hard time prompting conversation, but expected everyone to contribute. Nice guy!

Definitely my least favorite course I've taken in college so far due to her large reading requirements and very harsh grading system. Professor Wake also has mandatory attendance and pop quizzes which make her course even more challenging to pass, would recommend avoiding her classes unless it's required for your major.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Beware of pop quizzes--Tough grader

comment: You'll have to do the readings before class, though you can probably get away with just reading the conclusions. But her lectures are very engaging and the class is discussion based. She is very experienced and eloquent. Be ready to write and convey ideas with nuance
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: I took LB133 with Dr. Wake Fall 2017 as a freshman. Looking back, her course has had a great impact on my current reading and writing skills. Yes, she is tough. She knows who you are in the class (participation grade  very accurate). I owe it to her for drastically improving my engagement. I look forward to future classes with her.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Professor Wake outlines a very vigorous course to prepare you for higher level HPS courses. The readings are relevant to medical ethics and she has an immense understanding of the content. On the downside, she is a tough grader with often no feedback. She will never give 100s on assignments. Getting a 4.0 is very difficult but not impossible.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: The class ran smoothly and discussion was challenging and engaging. Probably one of the most well-run classes I've taken at MSU. Her grading scale can throw you off so be warned: only a handful of points stand between a 4.0 and a 1.0. Used the course pack daily. No out of class papers, just in-class essay exams and a group presentation.
This class was a lot of fun, a lot of laughs and a lot of work. I learned a lot though. He is very knowledgeable and is willing to help you if you take initiative.
He is helpful and knows what he is talking about. He was very helpful at all times, even when he was busy and he shows major interest in every dairy topic.
He is really helpful and fair if you go to his office and talk to him. You learn a lot from a practical stand point.
No Comments
Solid teacher

Never been so bored in all of my life.  Literally torture to endure his lectures.  Awful, awful, awful.  I have never experienced anything like hearing him speak - it's beyond words. Feel very sorry if you have to endure him.

Do not take this class. Not only was i not interested in the topic he was a terrible lecturer and class was pointless. I almost never attended because i could not handle sitting through more than 20min without falling asleep. It is a waste of your time.
DO NOT TAKE THIS CLASS!

This man took a simple ISS class and turned it into hell.  He was a worthless professor.  I learned nothing and gained nothing from his class.  My friend had the same class with a different professor and had a great time.  I felt physical pain at the thought of going to this class.  DO NOT TAKE HIS CLASS!
Great professor! Explains class material well and incorporates humor to keep things interesting.
ratingTags: Respected--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: The course itself was fairly easy. However she looks for course materials to be quoted HEAVILY in all papers. Several of my cohorts lost points on assignments due to lack of quotes from the assigned readings.
She's great...I would take her for every class if it was possible. So helpful and keeps class interesting.
An awesome professor!  She even made a 3hr. theory class interesting!

If you get a choice for which professor to take for PHY 231, try to take it with Professor Doleans.  His class was my first encounter with physics, ever, and I was impressed with the clarity of his teaching methods and explanations. He is extremely helpful with preparing students for exams. He makes showing up to exam review well worth your time :)

Marc is a great professor.  He is very smart and cares about teaching his students.  He is the most helpful professor I've ever had.  He makes all of the exams for all three sections and gives hints about what to focus on during exam reviews.  Too bad he doesn't teach PHY 232.
No Comments

Marc is a wonderful professor. His class when I took it was at 8 am so unfortunately I missed quite a few so I wish I would have attended more, but you will not find a more helpful, enthusiastic person to help you with physics. He communicates his ideas very well and he is always willing to take time out of his schedule to give you personal help :)

- Typically starts class 5 minutes late due to technological reasons - Typically keeps lecturing 2-3 minutes after class ends - Sits down at her computer for entire class period, does not ever stand or draw on the board - Very disorganized lecturer, active listening is difficult because she goes off on tangents every class - Exams are open note

The class is 3 hours long, but only 30 minutes of each class is actually used in an instructional manner. The instructor meanders so much during class that it is hard to maintain your attention on the topic at hand. In office hours, the instructor can explain concepts well; however, the instructor is really bad at lecturing.

I was very afraid of this class, since I hadn't taken math or stats in years. But she was helpful, clear and organized. Her annotated slides from lecture were posted on ANGEL; that was a GREAT help. Also lets you do homework in groups, which helped as well. She's very friendly and easy to ask questions of in class or out of class. Best teacher!
Rashad is a great teacher and makes chemistry fun. The exams are pretty hard and I suggest you buy the lecture notes!

He was terrible. His notes were hard to follow and he never explained the stuff you really needed to know. Basically, the professor explained the easy stuff,gave the bare skin and bones to the class and you had to struggle to learn the rest.
he makes chemistry sooo much easier & I took it in the summer with no problems. He's very helpful and he knows his stuff!

he is funny and teaches clearly. its not his fault if you do poorly. plus an 80%is a 4.0, so no complaining.you just have to take notes and STUDY! like every cem class youll have, but he is a good prof to have for it
really good teacher.. gives really good examples to help you understand the concepts.. and makes lecture as interesting as chemistry can possibly be
He's a cool guy. He's laid back and i like that alot
He does stick right to what's in the notes, but that's really all you need to know. Uses really good examples. I really like his laid back style of lecturing.

He is not a bad teacher at all, you just have to be interested in chemistry to follow him. Some claim that he is "too laid back", but those people are just too irresponsible to listen and learn. I personally love Rashad.
No Comments

This teacher completely taught right out of the book that another professor wrote.  So, good luck on trying to learn chemistry if you can't learn right out of the book.  This class is hard as it is...but, with him teaching out of the book makes it even worse!!

Prof. Norman's lectures were extremely long and sometimes very mundane. There is a lot of reading in this class and the quizzes are pretty much directly from the book. However, the book is very long and can be boring.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment: The class is not too difficult if you read the book. There is not really any homework so your grades on the quizzes as well as the midterm and final exam is what your grade is completely based off of.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Lecture heavy

comment: Overall Dr. Norman was a great prof. He is very passionate about the subject and you can tell in the lectures. If you show to class and do the readings the class isn't very difficult. There isn't homework or really any assignments that you are graded on other than quizzes, midterm, and final.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: He seems very interested in the subject, and he does not expect too much from his students. He is probably my favorite professor. I really enjoyed the class. Sometimes I wish he would talk louder, so maybe sit near the front.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Dr. Norman is a great prof. Lectures can be dry some time but before each quiz/exam he will tell you exactly what you need to know and break it down for you. The reading is necessary but it's not challenging. Go to lectures and read and you'll be find, the class isn't too hard. I found that a lot of test questions were based on definitions.
ratingTags: Respected--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: He is a great professor but does tend to get off topic with stories or topics that he feels strongly about. He makes you sign in at the beginning of class and occasionally gives out extra credit for the people who don't leave early so go to class. There are a lot of quizzes but you will know in advance. READ THE TEXTBOOK and take clear notes.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring

comment: Attendance isn't mandatory, but you do get points towards your final grade for being there. You're graded on 6 quizzes (mostly based on chapter readings and extra article readings), a mid-term, a group project (super easy), and the final. He does lecture, but they always tend to be super light.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--Would take again

comment: The urban planning quizzes are hard, but if you read the book youll be fine
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Pretty good teacher, easy class as long as you keep up with the reading. GO TO THIS CLASS. Attendance is like 20% of your grade. Take good notes and especially on the videos since those will be on the final and midterm exams.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Pretty chill ISS. There are quizzes every other week, but as long as you read the chapters/review using his notes on D2L, you'll be perfectly fine. Attendance is mandatory, so you might as well go and get attendance points. You really don't have to listen to his lectures if you do read the material outside of class.
ratingTags: TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Easy class to pass if you pay attention, study, and go to class. He gives out quizzes but those help you understand the material. Also you watch a number of videos too which he'll test on. Definitely review the vocabulary in the book because those are what a majority of the questions are on. Overall, was my easiest class of the whole semester.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: If you are looking for a easy class to take for an elective this is NOT IT, He cares about urban planning a lot and is nice but assumes people know/care deeply about urban planning and has tricky tests.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Doesn't go over much test material in class but attendance is part of grade. Gives extra credit when people don't come such as for an exam review. As long as you read your book and go to lecture you should do fine.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: He does not go over much test material at all. The only reason I attend class is because it counts toward my grade.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: Pretty easy class if you need an ISS credit definitely take it with this guy. He says at the beginning of the year there will be pop quizzes but will email you two nights before or say in class what will be on the exam or quiz. The book has a lot of mistakes but you should read it he takes a lot of the questions right out of the book.

He says there will be pop quizzes but he always told us when a quiz would be and what would be on the quiz. If you read the chapters and don't fall behind you will be fine. If you sit in the front row he will talk to you and possibly call on you for answers. Come to class everyday he gives extra credit on days when people skip (days after quizzes).

If you go to class, read, and pay attention its an easy A. If you don't go to class and skips the quizzes you'll fail. There are about 5 quizzes all semester but he tells you what you need to know for each one. If you go to the quiz review the next day and more than half the class isn't there, he'll give out extra credit.

I loved this class. Norman is very passionate about what he teaches and very good at it. Class is mandatory, 20% of your grade, easy points. READ THE CHAPTERS INTENTLY! Otherwise you will not do well at all, quiz questions come from the chapters. He also likes to engage the class in conversation, and we watched some great videos, too.
go to class, it's a part of your grade! actually read the chapters in the book-the quizzes have alot of questions that come from the book
Professor Norman is an excellent teacher. He sincerely enjoys what he's doing and it shows. You will NEED to read the book and attend class regularly.  If you're looking for an EASY 4.0 HERE IT IS!!!
if u have reg attendance and improving test scores he'll most likely boost your GPA. You NEED your book. Almost all info on quizzes and exams come from the book

Dr. Norman engages with the class, is enthusiastic & is interested in his own material which makes learning it more interesting.  He keeps the studnts involved and is always askin for their opinions. Some topics result in fun heated debates. The class had a little common sense knowledge but was pretty interesting.  One of the better ISS classes
As long as you go to class and pay attention to the videos, you will do well. This class tends to be very repeatative with the course material.
Loved her!  She is fair.  She only asks you what she lectures.  It is important to attend class.  If you attend class everyday and listen, you will do fine.

Adrienne gives off the vibe that she's an easy instructor that takes the class as a joke. The test was surprisingly difficult and her grading system is unfair and lengthy. Please do yourself a favor and take this class with someone else.
No Comments
Assan is one of the better TAs I have ever had. He is helpful, courteous, and smart. I would genuinely recommend taking one of Assan's classes; you will not be disappointed.

Joy is wonderful. She gives you so much freedom with how to complete the assignments. Getting a good grade is easy, I got a 3.0 without much effort. Also, she brought in cookies at the end of the semester.

Fantastic teacher! I loved Joy and she may be the best teacher I have ever had. Her grading scale looks scary when you see it but she grades easy. I received a 4.0 and I hate writing. She made this class fun and is a really cool person. She actually cares about the students and how they do! If you need to take WRA, take Durding!
Professor Durding is very down to Earth and has a very sharp wit. You will actually want to go to her class and her assignments give you an immense level of freedom.
I took Jason for intro. psychology a long time ago. He was excellent, and I wish that he would teach more.
I took this class a while ago, and really enjoyed it. I thought that Jason was really good and cared for the students.
Real ish right here.

Most unresponsive instructor I have ever seen. Sends out confused emails that do not answer questions. Fails to reply in timely manner to requests for information. Assignment drop boxes either are not posted or are mislabeled. Assignment deadlines are not made clear. Subjective grading. If you agree with his views, you are home free. If not, beware
EAD 822 was a great class. Dr. Dunbar is a great resource. Don't leave MSU without taking one of his classes.

Although it took me a few class periods to warm up to his teaching style (he has a tendency to ramble and is, at times, difficult to follow), Professor Johnsen is a quality professor who truly cares for his students. He is very passionate about his classes, and facilitates productive and interesting discussion, leaving room for students' opinions.

Johnsen is so sweet, and he's really passionate about Irish and British literature. He tends to ramble--but if you don't pay attention, you'll miss some of the world's best jokes from the world's most unassuming guy. He's genuinely interested in your interpretation of things, which is nice.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Caring--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: If you showed up to class it was extra credit that went towards your overall grade in the course. The class is not hard but very interesting. Its all on poems and you can tell that the prof really loves them. He grades on if you think/analyze a poem in a meaningful way not just the way he thinks about the poem.
ratingTags: Respected--Caring--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: This class was not hard at all. You definitely have to do the papers, and at least read the spark notes for the books he assigns.  He is very hard to understand when he talks, he really mumbles.  He is pretty lenient about due dates, but in class he talks about things that are not relevant to class at all.

This class was a total joke. Why did I pay $500 for it! A summer class, three hours a day twice a week for five weeks (3 credits), he let us go every day after forty minutes. Other students were happy with that, I thought it was pathetic. Papers came back with NO markings whatsoever, just the grade ("A", but still).

Felt bad for the man: he lost our interest/attention by the third class period. Hard of hearing, and didn't speak loud enough for us to understand him. Rambled. Heavy reading (Ulysses in 12 days). Undefined grading system: liked the topic = got a higher grade. Would've dropped the class the first week if I knew it would be like this.
I took his class at Dartmouth College - he is a visiting professor. Awesome
ratingTags: Hilarious--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Henry was my favorite professor that I took this semester. He is kind, funny, and definitely interested in what he is teaching. Some people say that he was confusing in terms of what he expected from students, but he spells it all out very clearly what you need to do to get a certain grade, and if you have questions you just need to ask.

He's a great professor, that's no doubt. He's got some great stories and the class itself isn't bad. It's just - he's very confusing about what he wants and doesn't want, and often doesn't answer questions straight when asked. Requirements for the class are confusing, but it's a fun class.
No Comments
Fun, easy professor. Sometimes difficult to go to class because material isn't difficult, but he does require attendance. Very helpful and interested in his field.

Prof Beck obviously loves his job. He tries to be "one of the students" and is very helpful if you need to talk to him about class related things, internships, etc. He would be a good person to keep in contact with for future internship/job opportunities I think. However, the class is pretty boring and attendance is mandatory.

Very difficult grader and has a voice that will put you to sleep, but explains things very well and helps quite a bit if you take advantage of it. Not a bad teacher, but a very strict grader so beware.

Had an independent study with.  Explanations were useless, help was virtually non-existent.  One day I actually got more insight out of 'discussing' a problem with a spider on the wall near my computer.  Avoid at all costs.
Lecture-slides are always perfect, and he explains things crystal clear. The class kept me so interested that I didn't want to miss a single class and 4.0 this class.

Class was hard, but it's supposed to be. Lots of quizzes and micro-assignments, but that sort of thing is the only way to encourage the wrote memorization of AP style, which is the most important and professionally essential thing I got from JRN 200.
It's hard, but it's JRN 200, it's supposed to be hard! Nancy's great and SO nice.

She makes this class impossible.  She does, however, know a lot of useful things and has good connections; too bad that she is a horrible teacher.  She has a quiz every day and she is the worst grader EVER!  I recommend getting out of this class if you can, I wish I could have.

Just because you know how a subject well does NOT mean you know how to TEACH. She definitely knows her stuff, but she was so unorganized and the class overall sucked. Ruined my GPA. Stay away if at all possible.

Easy class, but Donna talks about herself and all her achievements 24/7. Gets annoying fast, but overall she's nice and a fair grader

comment: Nice, butI'd avoid any classes having to do with writing. Shewith high school students, and she kinda expects the same thing from us as she does from them. A great deal of hand-holding, and she either expects far too much of her students, or far too little, with no in between. In a class about social identity, she only cared about race.
ratingTags: Participation matters

comment: Donna is a sweet professor, and a great person to do racial identity work with, especially if Cuba is involved. She can be frustrating at times though, and tends to overextend deadlines to the point where the end of the semester is far too stressful for students than it needs to be.
ratingTags: Inspirational--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Donna is quite possible my favorite professor. After I took her class, i was so inspired by her and her outlook on teaching, education, social justice and equality. She works hard to build relationships with her students and often checks in to make sure everything is working. I love her! take her class!!!

Donna is so sweet! I loved her class! She helps you out immensely, gives you plenty of time and examples in order to complete the assignments. She is very lenient with grading, always in a good mood, and willing to engage in outside of class discussions. She is well worth your time.
No Comments

I loved Dr. Harris. There are two exams and a term paper, you can use your study guides on the exams, but DO NOT rely on only that! I did that the first exam and found I didn't have enough time to finish because I was too busy searching for answers. There is also a term paper that is an easy 100% if you do all that is instructed. Cutest prof ever!
ratingTags: Caring--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Graded only by 2 exams and a paper, but offers lots of SONA extra credit. Very nice and considerate, brings snacks to class all the time, will work to build a personal relationship with you and help you out. Get to use your very lengthy review guide that he gives you on exams, with any notes you want on that. Book is not really necessary to do well
ratingTags: GRADED BY FEW THINGS--EXTRA CREDIT--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Avoid at all costs!

ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Amazing lectures

comment: Funny guy. Assignments online that require reading the textbook. Easy 4.0 if you do all the work. Exams are online so you can use notes!
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Hilarious

comment: This was an online class and it was so easy. If you do the assignments, you will pass with flying colors. My only criticism for Professor Kiuchi is that she did not engage with us students at all. I know it was online, but some check in emails would have been nice.
ratingTags: Clear grading criteria

comment: Easiest class I have ever taken at MSU. Literally show up you pass
Gives lots of extra credit opportunities, 3 open book tests, doesn't take attendance every day.

I liked the class. It's not an easy 4.0 but Dr Kiuchi will help you if you email him. Just put time into it. You listen to his lecture and do the assignments. You will get a good grade. If you have to take ISS, this is the class to take.

The class was good. Just put time into it. Instead of being in a classroom for 2 or 3 hours a week, you just listen to his lectures online and do assignments for a few hours a week. If you do the work he tells you to do, you will be fine.

I don't know why anyone is complaining about this professor. I took his IAH course over the summer online and it was the easiest thing. You do have to watch lectures that take time but the book reading isn't even necessary. I would buy the books though bc you will want to refer to them for writing assignments or for the exam. Put time in. Simple!
I think he is great. I enjoy the class.
Why the hell would he do 91% or above as a 4.0? why does he has to be so different than other professors? we are not UM. So lower the expectations and just let us have the 4.0.

I am taking his ISS course right now and it is the worst! I have to say something.We have so much reading to do every week and on top of that we have 2-3 online lectures to watch. He only opens it for 4 days. It sucks. I have a life and I don't want to sit there and read his crap all day long. One of the book is not even related to the course.
I was never clear on what he wanted written there is like 5 papers back to back every one has to be 5-6 pages ( take a different WRA class)
He helps you a lot. This is the best class you could take with WRA.

Really helpful. You will be a great writer after this class. It's a required class, but he makes it as fun as anyone could possibly do. If you work a lot, he will help you a lot. I got a sense he wants you to succeed but if you show him you're dedicated, he will help you even more. He's available face to face or email. He is great.
Horrible professor. He was never clear on his assignments, and not very helpful at all. Be prepared to write many papers, 4~6 pages each.

He's awesome! Very helpful class, informative and helps tremendously with writing papers. He's funny, (at least he is to me) and finds interesting was to incorporate class lessons with things like The Big Bang Theory, or other odd things MSU professors don't usually do. Very interesting class on Race, be ready to write like a pro once your done!
amazing
Great Professor
Great Professor Best ever
Best professor ever.
Pretty easy class, got a 4.0. Helps with papers a lot

Really solid prof. Very knowledgeable and helpful in office hours. Readings can be a bit burdensome at times, but are usually interesting and definitely helpful for the exams. Paper is actually helpful in better understanding the different theories.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: really good prof. If you tell him something once he'll remember it. Office hours are really a good place to go if you dont understand
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Caring

comment: Good prof overall. Highly suggest going to office hours. He clearly knows his stuff, just not the most exciting lecturer. Read. Read. Read the books. His classes are book heavy but you really do get a lot out of his classes. Overall I'd recommend him.
Great professor. Easy to understand and always willing to help students with what can be a very challenging introductory course.

Class was engaging and to the point. He was one of the course leaders, so he knew and would tell you exactly what they were expecting for each assignment. Lots of office hours and very interested in what he teaches. A lot of reading is required, but he is generally able to link the concepts discussed to current events.

There is a lot of reading material and class discussions. He is pretty cool but he doesn't really answer questions very clearly. He answers your questions with a question because he wants you to find the answer or make your own decision about it. Overall, he is very informative and it was an interesting class.
